00:11:04,850 --> 00:11:08,700
by others either
from the group-level,

251
00:11:08,700 --> 00:11:12,390
so you see r and x
and r and x here.

252
00:11:12,390 --> 00:11:15,050
So by the group and
the others also then

253
00:11:15,050 --> 00:11:18,530
have permissions for this.

254
00:11:18,530 --> 00:11:21,155
You can google all the
different numeric commands,

255
00:11:21,155 --> 00:11:23,530
but to explain like what this
means because again, we did

256
00:11:23,530 --> 00:11:27,260
chmod 755, basically,
the digits themselves

257
00:11:27,260 --> 00:11:31,560
stand for read, write,
execute, or no permissions.

258
00:11:31,560 --> 00:11:38,240
So a 0 is no permissions,
1 is execute permissions,

259
00:11:38,240 --> 00:11:42,150
a 2 is write permissions,
and a 4 is read permissions.

260
00:11:42,150 --> 00:11:45,760
And so what ends up happening is
the first number in that list,

261
00:11:45,760 --> 00:11:48,570
so if we go again here,
this first number, the 7,

262
00:11:48,570 --> 00:11:53,190
is the sum of 4
plus 2 plus 1, which

263
00:11:53,190 --> 00:11:54,780
means that it's
given read, which

264
00:11:54,780 --> 00:11:59,070
was 4 points, 2
points for write,

265
00:11:59,070 --> 00:12:01,060
and then 1 point for execute.

266
00:12:01,060 --> 00:12:02,830
So it's a clever
trick to say, OK.

267
00:12:02,830 --> 00:12:04,570
Well, whatever the
sum of this is,

268
00:12:04,570 --> 00:12:06,670
that'll specify the
level of permissions.

269
00:12:06,670 --> 00:12:11,680
So since the first digit is 7,
that means the owner or sorry.

270
00:12:11,680 --> 00:12:14,980
The user has read, write,
and execute permissions.

271
00:12:14,980 --> 00:12:18,300
This second number
being 5 means that we

272
00:12:18,300 --> 00:12:25,420
are summing the 1 and the 4
because 1 plus 4 gives us 5.

273
00:12:25,420 --> 00:12:29,820
That means we have read
and execute permissions.

274
00:12:29,820 --> 00:12:31,620
If we had done-- oh.

275
00:12:31,620 --> 00:12:33,180
Let's go back here.

276
00:12:33,180 --> 00:12:36,700
If we had made this last digit
of 4, then that would have said,

277
00:12:36,700 --> 00:12:40,123
well, 4 is just
read permissions.

278
00:12:40,123 --> 00:12:41,290
So that would have said, OK.

279
00:12:41,290 --> 00:12:44,700
Well, let's run it really
quick and just show that.

280
00:12:44,700 --> 00:12:49,600
So now you can see that the
owner or the user has read,

281
00:12:49,600 --> 00:12:53,370
write, and execute
permissions, the group has read

282
00:12:53,370 --> 00:12:54,370
and execute permissions.

283
00:12:54,370 --> 00:12:56,100
So that's the sum of 5.

284
00:12:56,100 --> 00:12:58,860
And then the read
permissions only

285
00:12:58,860 --> 00:13:01,540
for others on this computer.

286
00:13:01,540 --> 00:13:04,360
So you'll see this run in
a bunch of different ways.

287
00:13:04,360 --> 00:13:09,690
Remember, when we ran this
just on our ec2 instance or ssh

288
00:13:09,690 --> 00:13:12,930
into our ec2 instance, it said,
you have to run chmod 400,

289
00:13:12,930 --> 00:13:14,820
if you're on a Mac, for example.

290
00:13:14,820 --> 00:13:16,570
On the windows, we
didn't have to do this.

291
00:13:16,570 --> 00:13:18,360
But if you think
about what that means,

292
00:13:18,360 --> 00:13:22,980
is when we did
chmod 400, whatever,

293
00:13:22,980 --> 00:13:27,660
whatever our pem key
was, that set read

294
00:13:27,660 --> 00:13:31,680
permissions for the user account
but only read permissions,

295
00:13:31,680 --> 00:13:33,790
and then 0 for anybody else.

296
00:13:33,790 --> 00:13:35,620
That means nobody
else on that machine,

297
00:13:35,620 --> 00:13:37,470
no matter what user
account they are on

298
00:13:37,470 --> 00:13:40,000
or how they're logged
into that machine,

299
00:13:40,000 --> 00:13:44,170
nobody else has access to read,
write, or execute for that file.

300
00:13:44,170 --> 00:13:46,720
And the user account only
has read permissions.

301
00:13:46,720 --> 00:13:49,980
So that's a way to ensure that
I don't overwrite things or mess

302
00:13:49,980 --> 00:13:51,540
anything up in any way.

303
00:13:51,540 --> 00:13:55,300
So permissions can be very,
very helpful to control, modify,

304
00:13:55,300 --> 00:13:56,680
edit, and all that good stuff.

305
00:13:56,680 --> 00:14:01,520
And that's exactly how we
do it just via that chmod.

306
00:14:01,520 --> 00:14:05,820
We can also change
ownership of a file.

307
00:14:05,820 --> 00:14:07,820
So if we say--
because right now,

308
00:14:07,820 --> 00:14:11,060
this is saying this user
has read, write, and execute

309
00:14:11,060 --> 00:14:11,830
permissions.

310
00:14:11,830 --> 00:14:14,210
If we had another user
on here, though, they

311
00:14:14,210 --> 00:14:15,410
wouldn't be treated--

312
00:14:15,410 --> 00:14:17,570
or their user account,
since let's say,

313
00:14:17,570 --> 00:14:19,845
they were part of
our group, they

314
00:14:19,845 --> 00:14:21,720
would only have read
and execute permissions.

315
00:14:21,720 --> 00:14:23,845
But maybe we're saying,
actually, it's this other--

316
00:14:23,845 --> 00:14:25,790
or this other user's file now.

317
00:14:25,790 --> 00:14:28,020
We want to transfer the
ownership over to them.

318
00:14:28,020 --> 00:14:32,100
So the way we can do
that is we can say, OK.

319
00:14:32,100 --> 00:14:35,310
Well-- and there's not
another user on this account.

320
00:14:35,310 --> 00:14:38,840
So I'm just going to use the
root account as an example.

321
00:14:38,840 --> 00:14:44,420
But what this says now is I want
to move the ownership, change

322
00:14:44,420 --> 00:14:46,310
ownership chown.

323
00:14:46,310 --> 00:14:48,770
I want to change the
ownership from the root

324
00:14:48,770 --> 00:14:51,860
or from who it is right
now to the root account.

325
00:14:51,860 --> 00:14:54,920
So if I rerun this
ls dash l, you'll

326
00:14:54,920 --> 00:14:58,380
see now that instead of it
showing the owner being Ubuntu,

327
00:14:58,380 --> 00:15:01,740
it'll show the owner
as the root account.

328
00:15:01,740 --> 00:15:05,052
Now, Ubuntu user account
happens to also have

329
00:15:05,052 --> 00:15:06,010
root-level permissions.

330
00:15:06,010 --> 00:15:10,250
So that's why we didn't have the
actual permissions themselves

331
00:15:10,250 --> 00:15:10,750
change.

332
00:15:10,750 --> 00:15:14,070
But notice that the
ownership has changed.

333
00:15:14,070 --> 00:15:16,170
Also, to take a
step back, you'll

334
00:15:16,170 --> 00:15:21,390
see me use this
sudo command a lot.

335
00:15:21,390 --> 00:15:23,650
That's not because
it's best practice,

336
00:15:23,650 --> 00:15:26,920
but because of, oftentimes,
what we're doing requires this.

337
00:15:26,920 --> 00:15:29,370
So it stands for super user do.

338
00:15:29,370 --> 00:15:31,890
It basically gives you
root-level permissions

339
00:15:31,890 --> 00:15:34,020
for a specific command.

340
00:15:34,020 --> 00:15:39,630
So to back out and
explain this a little bit,

341
00:15:39,630 --> 00:15:42,360
every user on this
machine-- or think

342
00:15:42,360 --> 00:15:44,520
about your personal computer.

343
00:15:44,520 --> 00:15:46,800
On your personal computer,
you have a user account

344
00:15:46,800 --> 00:15:48,160
that's maybe your name.

345
00:15:48,160 --> 00:15:50,280
You log in to that user
account, and then you

346
00:15:50,280 --> 00:15:51,760
can do whatever you want.

347
00:15:51,760 --> 00:15:55,320
But technically speaking, there
needs to be an admin that has

348
00:15:55,320 --> 00:15:57,213
"complete" ownership
over your computer.

349
00:15:57,213 --> 00:15:59,380
They can do anything and
everything to the computer.

350
00:15:59,380 --> 00:16:00,780
And best practice
would typically

351
00:16:00,780 --> 00:16:03,930
have us not use the
root-level account always

352
00:16:03,930 --> 00:16:05,880
for every little
thing we need to do.

353
00:16:05,880 --> 00:16:08,740
So that's why we don't actually
log in to that admin account.

354
00:16:08,740 --> 00:16:09,660
You sometimes see
this when you go

355
00:16:09,660 --> 00:16:11,110
to install some software,
something like that.

356
00:16:11,110 --> 00:16:12,960
It's like you need
to put in a password

357
00:16:12,960 --> 00:16:14,627
because you need
admin-level permissions

358
00:16:14,627 --> 00:16:16,220
or root-level
permissions to do that.

359
00:16:16,220 --> 00:16:17,220
That's what it's saying.

360
00:16:17,220 --> 00:16:20,640
Is basically we need to
take a step back or ensure

361
00:16:20,640 --> 00:16:22,800
that this person
installing the software

362
00:16:22,800 --> 00:16:24,910
has complete control
of this machine.

363
00:16:24,910 --> 00:16:27,250
And so you have to do
it at the root level.

364
00:16:27,250 --> 00:16:30,540
And that's what we're doing here
with this S-U-D-O, sudo command.

365
00:16:30,540 --> 00:16:31,990
Is we're saying, OK.

366
00:16:31,990 --> 00:16:34,560
For this one command, I'm
running this change ownership.

367
00:16:34,560 --> 00:16:36,780
I want to pretend
for one command

368
00:16:36,780 --> 00:16:39,390
that I am the root user account.

369
00:16:39,390 --> 00:16:41,178
If you do this on
your personal machine,

370
00:16:41,178 --> 00:16:42,970
sometimes, if you have,
for example, a Mac,

371
00:16:42,970 --> 00:16:45,180
you can use sudo
as well, I believe,

372
00:16:45,180 --> 00:16:48,990
you'll be prompted to use a
password or put in a password

373
00:16:48,990 --> 00:16:50,820
when you run that,
because you have

374
00:16:50,820 --> 00:16:53,190
to have complete
ownership of that machine

375
00:16:53,190 --> 00:16:54,660
to be able to do that.

376
00:16:54,660 --> 00:16:57,470
So that's what the sudo
command does there.

377
00:16:57,470 --> 00:16:59,220
And you'll see this,
again, a lot of times

378
00:16:59,220 --> 00:17:01,320
when we have to do
things at a lower level

379
00:17:01,320 --> 00:17:02,900
or at a root level
on the machine.

380
00:17:05,550 --> 00:17:07,329
A couple other
helpful tips here.

381
00:17:07,329 --> 00:17:10,230
We'll clear it out for a second,
so I can see it a little easier.

382
00:17:10,230 --> 00:17:13,500
We have the ps
command, which the ps

383
00:17:13,500 --> 00:17:17,230
command lists all the processes
that are running on our system.

384
00:17:17,230 --> 00:17:20,010
So, for example, if we run--

385
00:17:20,010 --> 00:17:21,930
let's actually go back to our--

386
00:17:21,930 --> 00:17:22,839
not that it matters.

387
00:17:22,839 --> 00:17:26,770
But if I run this now, I
can-- and so I'm sorry.

388
00:17:26,770 --> 00:17:29,370
I just ran ps aux here.

389
00:17:29,370 --> 00:17:33,270
This printed out all of
the processes running here

390
00:17:33,270 --> 00:17:34,650
on my computer.

391
00:17:34,650 --> 00:17:37,278
So every little thing
here that is possibly

392
00:17:37,278 --> 00:17:39,570
running in the background--
you see, most of this stuff

393
00:17:39,570 --> 00:17:43,320
is using 0% of the CPU.

394
00:17:43,320 --> 00:17:45,340
This is all
happening right here.

395
00:17:45,340 --> 00:17:48,070
Or I can actually access
all these individual things.

396
00:17:48,070 --> 00:17:50,940
This can be very helpful, if
you run into a situation where

397
00:17:50,940 --> 00:17:53,250
something is really
freezing up a computer

398
00:17:53,250 --> 00:17:54,960
or is eating up a
lot of resources

399
00:17:54,960 --> 00:17:56,740
and you want to
kill the process.

400
00:17:56,740 --> 00:18:00,850
Then you want to be able
to identify the PID here,

401
00:18:00,850 --> 00:18:02,990
the process ID, and specify it.

402
00:18:02,990 --> 00:18:05,490
And so you can say things like,
for example, if I wanted to,

403
00:18:05,490 --> 00:18:08,245
and I'm not going to
because I'm not running

404
00:18:08,245 --> 00:18:09,370
anything in the background.

405
00:18:09,370 --> 00:18:12,700
So let's say, for example, I
wanted to kill that process,

406
00:18:12,700 --> 00:18:14,528
I would run kill,
and I'm not actually

407
00:18:14,528 --> 00:18:15,820
going to put it in real number.

408
00:18:15,820 --> 00:18:20,100
But let's say I had a process
that was number 6,000.

409
00:18:20,100 --> 00:18:22,620
Then I would run kill 6000.

410
00:18:22,620 --> 00:18:24,870
And that would end that process.

411
00:18:24,870 --> 00:18:29,490
It's like forced quitting
on Macs or like the--

412
00:18:29,490 --> 00:18:31,630
I forget the equivalent
it is on Windows now.

413
00:18:31,630 --> 00:18:35,020
But ending the process or
stopping the process here.

414
00:18:35,020 --> 00:18:39,420
So that's one way to directly
shut down a process that's

415
00:18:39,420 --> 00:18:41,580
running in the background.

416
00:18:41,580 --> 00:18:44,430
Another way to monitor
usage is to run top.

417
00:18:44,430 --> 00:18:46,890
So again, I'll just
show here what I did.

418
00:18:46,890 --> 00:18:49,830
So T-O-P and then hit Enter.

419
00:18:49,830 --> 00:18:52,060
And that'll bring
up a live view.

420
00:18:52,060 --> 00:18:53,590
So this is constantly changing.

421
00:18:53,590 --> 00:18:56,610
You'll see this constantly
change every couple of seconds.

422
00:18:56,610 --> 00:18:58,273
And that'll show
you actively what's

423
00:18:58,273 --> 00:18:59,440
being done on your computer.

424
00:18:59,440 --> 00:19:01,070
So what's using
memory, how much memory

425
00:19:01,070 --> 00:19:04,490
it's using, what percent of
the CPU that's being utilized.

426
00:19:04,490 --> 00:19:06,433
So top can be a
really helpful command

427
00:19:06,433 --> 00:19:07,850
to just keep an
eye on things that

428
00:19:07,850 --> 00:19:09,800
are running in the background.

429
00:19:09,800 --> 00:19:13,740
And then if I want
to back out of top,

430
00:19:13,740 --> 00:19:16,970
then all I need to do
is hit Control and C.

431
00:19:16,970 --> 00:19:18,690
And that'll stop the process.

432
00:19:18,690 --> 00:19:21,570
So that's a way I can
get back to my console.

433
00:19:21,570 --> 00:19:26,450
And Control - C is the go-to
default to shut down something

434
00:19:26,450 --> 00:19:29,840
that's actively running or like
eating up your terminal window

435
00:19:29,840 --> 00:19:32,580
here.

436
00:19:32,580 --> 00:19:34,950
Another helpful tool here.

437
00:19:34,950 --> 00:19:37,850
If you want to see some
of your network details,

438
00:19:37,850 --> 00:19:42,176
like IP address, for example, or
any other network information,

439
00:19:42,176 --> 00:19:42,718
oop.

440
00:19:42,718 --> 00:19:44,010
I have config is not installed.

441
00:19:44,010 --> 00:19:46,623
Let's do IP address.

442
00:19:46,623 --> 00:19:47,540
Is that one installed?

443
00:19:47,540 --> 00:19:48,040
Yeah.

444
00:19:48,040 --> 00:19:49,223
So IP addr.

445
00:19:49,223 --> 00:19:51,390
And we'll show how to install
something in a second.

446
00:19:51,390 --> 00:19:52,973
But I don't want to
do that right now.

447
00:19:55,610 --> 00:19:58,440
And this is your local host.

448
00:19:58,440 --> 00:20:00,310
This is showing your
local IP address.

449
00:20:00,310 --> 00:20:01,620
This 172.

450
00:20:01,620 --> 00:20:03,960
And then it should
show your public,

451
00:20:03,960 --> 00:20:06,547
or might not show
your public as well.

452
00:20:06,547 --> 00:20:08,380
I have to use if config
to show your public.

453
00:20:08,380 --> 00:20:10,672
But either way, you can see
your local IP address here.

454
00:20:10,672 --> 00:20:14,130
This 172.31 and all
that good stuff.

455
00:20:14,130 --> 00:20:15,190
ubuntu@ip.

456
00:20:15,190 --> 00:20:17,080
So you can see it
matches up here.

457
00:20:17,080 --> 00:20:19,870
The .31.29.34.

458
00:20:19,870 --> 00:20:23,940
So that's one way to check that.

459
00:20:23,940 --> 00:20:27,480
If you ever want to check
that your network is connected

460
00:20:27,480 --> 00:20:32,790
to the internet,
or just to see how

461
00:20:32,790 --> 00:20:36,460
the speeds, the
ping to other sites,

462
00:20:36,460 --> 00:20:40,840
you can run ping and then put in
a website name like google.com.

463
00:20:40,840 --> 00:20:44,823
And that'll tell you how long
it takes to ping a website.

464
00:20:44,823 --> 00:20:46,990
If this didn't return
anything or returned an error,

465
00:20:46,990 --> 00:20:49,350
then you might know you have an
internet or a network connection

466
00:20:49,350 --> 00:20:49,850
issue.

467
00:20:49,850 --> 00:20:51,870
So it's just sending
little packets over there

468
00:20:51,870 --> 00:20:53,328
to see, basically,
how long does it

469
00:20:53,328 --> 00:20:55,105
take to communicate
to google.com?

470
00:20:55,105 --> 00:20:56,730
Right now, we're at
pretty consistently

471
00:20:56,730 --> 00:20:58,810
just short of 6 milliseconds.

472
00:20:58,810 --> 00:21:02,130
So again, a helpful tool
to quickly easily access

473
00:21:02,130 --> 00:21:03,036
that information.

474
00:21:06,300 --> 00:21:08,820
From there, we saw
just an example

475
00:21:08,820 --> 00:21:12,480
above where I had a
library or a function

476
00:21:12,480 --> 00:21:15,540
that I-- command that I wanted
to run that was installed.

477
00:21:15,540 --> 00:21:17,250
Another example
like htop is-- oh.

478
00:21:17,250 --> 00:21:18,460
Actually, htop is installed.

479
00:21:18,460 --> 00:21:19,930
So let's do it with ifconfig.

480
00:21:19,930 --> 00:21:25,560
So if I want to install a
package or a function, command,

481
00:21:25,560 --> 00:21:29,310
whatever it is, first off, I
need to know what it's called.

482
00:21:29,310 --> 00:21:32,310
In this case, if you remember,
when we ran ifconfig,

483
00:21:32,310 --> 00:21:34,360
it gave us a hint and said, hey.

484
00:21:34,360 --> 00:21:35,980
I don't think this is installed.

485
00:21:35,980 --> 00:21:38,670
So you should
probably install it.

486
00:21:38,670 --> 00:21:41,070
Way to do that,
relatively simple.

487
00:21:41,070 --> 00:21:43,883
So we're going to
use the sudo again.

488
00:21:43,883 --> 00:21:45,550
The first thing I'm
going to do, though,

489
00:21:45,550 --> 00:21:49,500
is run apt hyphen
get and then update.

490
00:21:49,500 --> 00:21:52,830
And what that does is it's
updating in the background

491
00:21:52,830 --> 00:21:57,690
all of the directories
that have listings

492
00:21:57,690 --> 00:22:01,450
of packages and libraries
that I can install.

493
00:22:01,450 --> 00:22:03,242
You don't have to
run this necessarily,

494
00:22:03,242 --> 00:22:04,200
but it's good practice.

495
00:22:04,200 --> 00:22:06,075
And you'll see me do
this a lot, to say, hey.

496
00:22:06,075 --> 00:22:07,980
Well, I want to
install this library.

